arch:property.oc:show_val: L33 is hard compacted fill below L32 surface. There may be some mudbrick here. We opened this locus after we cleared the surface from L32, we thought there would be some more mudbrick as seen in the redbrick wall with stone foundation in SW corner of the locus. At the NW corner there was some poorly preserved green mudbrick that is probably associated with the long thin red brick wall with 2 associated cobbles north of the red brick wall with cobble foundation at the SW corner of the locus. Closed locus 33 when we changed the surrounding feature loci, mudbrick wall with cobbles became L39, smaller red mudbrick wall with 2 cobbles became L38, surface became L37 and we extended the fill locus 34 to the border of the walls.
very compact flaky clay loam, possibly mudbrick debris
very compact clayey fill with mudbrick debris

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
